ut through the open window. The girl wears a dark hat, and both children wave enthusiastically toward the street below. A passerby briefly blurs across the foreground, but the children remain at the window, still waving.\n\nThe view opens out to a wider Western town square. Wooden wagons, stacked crates, barrels, burlap sacks, and low wooden buildings fill the dusty street. Several adults in casual modern clothing move around the wagons and storefronts, including people in light shirts, shorts, jeans, and blue sportswear. On the far left foreground, an older cowboy-looking man in a floppy tan hat, pale shirt, suspenders, and a dark neckerchief steps into view, looking across the scene as if surprised by all the non-cowboy clothing around him.\n\nLarge white on-screen text appears over the town scene: “Wrangler,” with the slogan beneath it, “IT DOESN’T JUST MEAN COWBOY ANYMORE.” Behind the text, three rugged cowboy figures gather in the foreground. The man on the left wears a tan hat, pale shirt, suspenders, and neckerchief, with one hand raised near his ear or the side of his head. The center man wears a light cowboy hat, red shirt, brown vest, and neck scarf, with a moustache and a weathered face. The man on the right wears a black cowboy hat, white shirt, gray vest, and red neckerchief, also with a moustache. They stand shoulder to shoulder, looking off toward the modernly dressed people with bemused, slightly confused expressions, while the Wrangler name and slogan remain prominent across the lower half of the image.",
